==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obi
<hw>O"bi</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. of African
origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A species of sorcery, probably of
African origin, practiced among the negroes of the West Indies.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>obe</asp> and <asp>obeah</asp>.]</altsp>
<rj><au>De Quincey.</au> <au>B. Edwards.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A charm or fetish.</def> <mark>[West Indies]</mark>
<rj><au>B. Edwards.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obi</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Obi
<hw>O"bi</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧"b⟦esl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Jap.]</ety>
<def>A sash, esp. the long belt-like broad sash of soft material worn by
women around the waist when wearing a traditional kimono, and usually
having a large bow at the back.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>Over this is bound the large sash (<qex>obi</qex>) which is the
chief article of feminine adornment.</q> <rj><qau>B. H.
Chamberlain.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obiism</ent>⟦br⟧
